                            <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 leading-tight">
                                Understanding Mortgage Rates: A Complete Guide for Buyers
                            </h1>

                            <div class="mb-8">
                                <img src="/images/mortgage-rates-guide.webp" alt="Mortgage rate chart and house keys"
                                    class="w-full h-80 object-cover rounded-lg shadow-lg" fetchpriority="high">
                            </div>

                            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
                                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Introduction</h2>
                                <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
                                    When buying a home, your mortgage rate is one of the most important factors. It
                                    determines your monthly payment and the total interest you'll pay over the life of
                                    the loan. Understanding how these rates work can save you thousands of dollars.
                                </p>

                                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">What Determines Your Rate?</h2>
                                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Several factors, both individual and economic, influence
                                    the mortgage rate you'll be offered.</p>
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                    <li><strong>Credit Score:</strong> The single most important factor. Better scores
                                        get lower rates.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Down Payment:</strong> A larger down payment can often lead to a lower
                                        interest rate.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Loan Term:</strong> Shorter terms (like 15 years) typically have lower
                                        rates than longer ones (like 30 years).</li>
                                    <li><strong>Economic Factors:</strong> Inflation, the Federal Reserve's actions, and
                                        the overall economy play a huge role.</li>
                                </ul>

                                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Fixed vs. Adjustable Rates</h2>
                                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Choosing between a fixed-rate and an adjustable-rate
                                    mortgage (ARM) is a major decision.</p>
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                    <li><strong>Fixed-Rate:</strong> Your interest rate and payment remain the same for
                                        the life of the loan.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Adjustable-Rate (ARM):</strong> Your rate is typically lower initially
                                        but can adjust up or down after a set period.</li>
                                </ul>

                                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
                                <p class="text-gray-700">
                                    Don't just take the first rate you're offered. Shop around with different lenders to
                                    ensure you're getting the best possible deal for your financial situation.
                                </p>
                            </div>
